Seven years late, the Hubble Space

"As near as we can tell, everything looks perfect," said astronaut Steve Hawley from the shuttle.
"Hubble's in its element and I'm delighted."
The telescope was supposed to be launched in 1983, but technical problems and the Challenger accident delayed its deployment.
said Truly, a former shuttle astronaut.
The telescope has two mirrors, one 94.5 inches in diameter, the other 12 inches.
Two of the instruments are cameras, two are spectrometers and one is a photometer.
In the cargo bay, the telescope receives electrical power from the shuttle.
